    tags: ["streaming", "disruption", "pivot"],
    content: "In 2007, Netflix was the undisputed king of DVD-by-mail, with over 7.5 million subscribers and a billion dollars in annual revenue. Reed Hastings had always viewed DVDs as a transitional format, and when broadband penetration reached a critical threshold, he made the bold decision to launch a streaming service — even though it meant cannibalizing the company's profitable core business. The initial streaming library was tiny (around 1,000 titles), the technology was unreliable, and the DVD business was still growing. Many board members and investors questioned the timing.\n\nThe most painful moment came in 2011, when Netflix attempted to separate its DVD and streaming businesses by creating a separate brand called Qwikster. The announcement was a communications disaster — customers were furious about price increases, confused about having two accounts, and felt that Netflix was abandoning them. Netflix lost 800,000 subscribers in a single quarter and the stock dropped 77%. Hastings publicly apologized and killed Qwikster, but the underlying strategic direction — prioritizing streaming — never wavered.\n\nWhat made Netflix's transition ultimately successful was their willingness to invest in original content. House of Cards in 2013 was the watershed moment — Netflix spent $100 million on two seasons of a show, greenlit entirely based on data about viewer preferences (users who watched the original UK version also watched David Fincher films and Kevin Spacey films). This data-driven approach to content commissioning was revolutionary in an industry that relied on pilot episodes and gut instinct. It gave Netflix a content library that no competitor could license away.\n\nThe Netflix case teaches product managers about the courage required for platform transitions. Hastings deliberately chose short-term pain for long-term positioning, and he was nearly fired for it. The lesson is not that every company should cannibalize its core business, but rather that the timing of technology transitions is everything. Move too early and you starve the business; move too late and you become Blockbuster. Netflix found the narrow window and had the organizational courage to leap through it, even when the landing was rough.",
