    content: "When Dylan Field dropped out of Brown University in 2012 to start Figma, the design tool market was dominated by Sketch on Mac and Adobe's Creative Suite. Both were desktop applications, both saved files locally, and both required designers to export and share screenshots when they wanted feedback. Field's thesis was that design was fundamentally a collaborative activity trapped in single-player tools. Building in the browser meant anyone with a URL could view, comment on, or edit a design — no downloads, no installations, no version conflicts.\n\nThe technical challenge was immense. Rendering a professional design tool in the browser required building a custom rendering engine in WebGL, because the DOM and Canvas APIs were too slow for complex design work. Figma's engineering team spent over three years building this foundation before launching publicly. The investment paid off: Figma could render complex designs at 60 frames per second in a browser tab, matching or exceeding the performance of native desktop applications.\n\nThe multiplayer collaboration feature — seeing other people's cursors in real time — was not just a technical showcase but a fundamental rethinking of the design workflow. Before Figma, design review meant scheduling a meeting, sharing screens, and hoping everyone was looking at the same version. With Figma, a PM could drop a comment directly on a button, a developer could inspect spacing values without asking, and a stakeholder could watch a design evolve in real time. This collapsed feedback cycles from days to minutes and made design accessible to non-designers in a way that desktop tools never could.\n\nFigma's growth strategy leveraged the same viral mechanics as Slack: it spread within organizations through shared links. Every time a designer sent a Figma URL to a PM or engineer for feedback, they were introducing a new user to the platform. This bottom-up adoption meant that by the time Adobe attempted to acquire Figma for $20 billion, the product had become so embedded in design workflows that the EU blocked the deal on competition grounds. For PMs, Figma demonstrates that the most powerful moat is not technology but workflow integration — when your product becomes the medium through which work happens, switching costs become nearly infinite.",
