    content: "Kevin Systrom and Mike Krieger originally built Burbn, a location-based check-in app that competed with Foursquare. The app was feature-rich — you could check in to locations, post plans, earn points, and share photos. But when Systrom analyzed user behavior, he noticed something striking: people were ignoring almost every feature except photo sharing. The check-ins, the plans, the points — all unused. Users just wanted to share photos with filters that made their phone snapshots look beautiful.\n\nThe decision to strip Burbn down to its single most-used feature and relaunch as Instagram was an act of extraordinary product discipline. Systrom and Krieger did not add more photo features; they subtracted everything else. The launch version of Instagram did exactly three things: take a photo, apply a filter, and share it. The entire flow from camera to posted photo took less than thirty seconds. In an era when mobile apps were racing to add features, Instagram's minimalism was radical.\n\nThe filters were the secret weapon. In 2010, smartphone cameras were mediocre, and most phone photos looked flat and unimpressive. Instagram's filters — X-Pro II, Earlybird, Lo-fi — transformed mundane snapshots into something that looked artistic and intentional. This was not just an aesthetic choice; it lowered the bar for sharing. People who would never post an unfiltered phone photo felt confident sharing a filtered one. The filters democratized visual expression in the same way that auto-tune democratized music production.\n\nInstagram's pivot offers one of the clearest lessons in product management: watch what users do, not what they say. No user asked for Burbn's features to be removed. No survey would have suggested killing everything except photos. But the usage data told an unmistakable story, and Systrom had the courage to follow it. The broader principle is that the best product decisions often involve subtraction rather than addition. Finding the one thing your users actually love and removing everything that distracts from it can be more powerful than any feature you could build.",
