    tags: ["viral loop", "email", "growth hack"],
    content: "In 1996, Sabeer Bhatia and Jack Smith were building one of the first web-based email services. Their investor, Tim Draper, suggested an idea that would become the most legendary growth hack in tech history: append a small tagline to every outgoing email that read \"PS: I Love You. Get your free email at Hotmail.\" The genius was that every email sent by a Hotmail user became an advertisement to the recipient, delivered in the most trusted context possible — a personal message from someone they knew.\n\nThe mechanics of the viral loop were elegant in their simplicity. A Hotmail user sends an email. The recipient sees the tagline and clicks the link. They sign up for their own Hotmail account. Now they start sending emails with the same tagline. Each new user became an involuntary evangelist, and the loop fed itself with zero marginal cost. Unlike traditional advertising, the \"ad\" was contextually relevant — if you received an email from Hotmail, you could see that it worked, that real people used it, and that it was free.\n\nThe growth was explosive. Hotmail went from zero to 12 million users in 18 months, at a time when the entire internet had roughly 70 million users. The service was growing at 20,000 new accounts per day within the first few months. Certain geographic markets exploded overnight — India became one of the largest user bases because a single user in a large social network could trigger a cascade of signups through family and business email chains. Microsoft acquired Hotmail for $400 million in 1997, recognizing the strategic value of owning the default email for millions of internet users.\n\nThe Hotmail case established the template for viral growth that every subsequent tech company has studied. The core insight is that the product itself can be the distribution channel — every act of using the product exposes new potential users to it. For product managers, the lesson is to look for natural moments in product usage where exposure to non-users occurs, and to make the path from exposure to signup as frictionless as possible. The most effective viral loops do not feel like marketing; they feel like a natural extension of the product experience.",
