    tags: ["onboarding", "retention", "aha moment"],
    content: "By 2009, Twitter had a massive problem hiding behind impressive signup numbers. Millions of people were creating accounts, tweeting once or twice, and never coming back. The product felt empty and confusing for new users — you signed up, saw a blank timeline, and had no idea what to do next. Twitter's growth team dug into the data and found a critical threshold: users who followed at least 30 accounts were dramatically more likely to become long-term active users. Below that number, the timeline was too sparse to be interesting. Above it, the constant stream of content created a compelling reason to return.\n\nThis insight led to a complete redesign of the onboarding flow. Instead of dropping new users onto an empty timeline and hoping they would figure it out, Twitter introduced a \"Suggested Users\" list that made it easy to follow interesting accounts in a single step. The list was curated by category — news, sports, entertainment, technology — and users could follow dozens of accounts with a few taps. The goal was to get every new user past the 30-follow threshold as quickly as possible, ensuring their first experience of the timeline felt rich and engaging.\n\nThe impact was immediate and dramatic. New user retention jumped significantly, and the monthly active user count grew from roughly 30 million to over 100 million within a year. The suggested users feature also created a powerful network effect: the accounts on the suggested list grew enormous followings, which made their content better (more resources, more effort), which made the platform more valuable for everyone. Celebrities and media organizations invested more in Twitter because they could see rapid follower growth, which in turn made the platform more attractive to new users.\n\nFor product managers, Twitter's suggested users story is the canonical example of identifying and engineering the \"aha moment.\" Every product has a threshold of engagement beyond which users become habitual — the key is finding that threshold through data analysis and then designing the onboarding experience to push every user past it as quickly as possible. The lesson also highlights that retention problems often masquerade as acquisition problems: Twitter did not need more signups; it needed new users to experience enough value in their first session to come back for a second.",
