    year: 2006,
    tags: ["content", "SEO", "inbound"],
    content: "Brian Halligan and Dharmesh Shah did not just build a marketing software company — they invented a category and named it. In 2006, they coined the term \"inbound marketing\" to describe a philosophy of attracting customers through valuable content rather than interrupting them with ads. This was not merely branding; it was a strategic masterstroke that positioned HubSpot as the authority on a movement rather than just another vendor in a crowded market. When people Googled \"inbound marketing,\" they found HubSpot. The company owned the definition, the methodology, and the tools.\n\nHubSpot's content strategy was extraordinarily comprehensive. They published a blog that became the most-read marketing publication on the internet, producing multiple articles per day on topics ranging from email subject lines to SEO strategy. They created free tools — a website grader that analyzed your site's performance and a CRM that was genuinely useful — that generated millions of leads. They wrote the definitive textbook on inbound marketing. They created a certification program (HubSpot Academy) that trained hundreds of thousands of marketers, each of whom became an evangelist for HubSpot's methodology and tools.\n\nThe certification program was particularly brilliant as a growth mechanism. Marketers who earned HubSpot certifications put them on their LinkedIn profiles and resumes, which served as ambient advertising to every recruiter and colleague who viewed their profile. When these certified marketers joined new companies, they advocated for HubSpot's tools because they already knew the platform. This created a self-perpetuating cycle: HubSpot educated marketers for free, those marketers became advocates, and those advocates brought HubSpot into new organizations.\n\nFor product managers, HubSpot's story illustrates the ultimate expression of content-led growth: do not just create content about your product; create the intellectual framework that makes your product the obvious solution. By defining the problem space (inbound vs. outbound marketing) and positioning themselves as the leader of the winning philosophy, HubSpot made the product sale almost an afterthought. The lesson is that the most durable competitive advantage is not a feature but a mindset — if you can change how your customers think about their problem, they will naturally choose your solution.",
