    year: 2006,
    tags: ["platform", "e-commerce", "ecosystem"],
    content: "Tobias Lutke built the first version of Shopify because he wanted to sell snowboards online and found every existing e-commerce solution frustrating. This origin story is important because it meant Shopify was built from the merchant's perspective, not the platform's. While Amazon was building a consumer marketplace where merchants were interchangeable commodities, Shopify made a deliberately different strategic choice: empower individual merchants to build their own brands, their own stores, and their own customer relationships. Shopify would be the infrastructure layer, invisible to the end consumer.\n\nThis positioning as the \"anti-Amazon\" resonated deeply with a growing segment of merchants who were tired of Amazon's commoditizing effects. On Amazon, merchants compete solely on price and reviews, with no ability to build brand loyalty — Amazon owns the customer relationship. On Shopify, merchants own everything: their domain, their design, their customer data, their email list. This fundamental difference attracted brands that cared about long-term customer relationships rather than short-term transactions, from small artisans to major brands like Gymshark, Allbirds, and Kylie Cosmetics.\n\nShopify's platform strategy extended beyond the core product. By building an app store and a partner ecosystem, Shopify enabled thousands of developers to build specialized tools — email marketing, inventory management, subscription billing — that extended the platform's capabilities. This created a flywheel: more merchants attracted more developers, who built more apps, which made the platform more capable, which attracted more merchants. Shopify also launched Shopify Payments (processing transactions directly), Shopify Capital (lending to merchants), and Shopify Fulfillment Network, each of which deepened the platform's value and increased switching costs.\n\nFor product managers, Shopify's story is a masterclass in platform positioning. The decision to empower merchants rather than compete with them was not just a feel-good mission statement — it was a structural strategy that created alignment between Shopify and its customers. When your success is directly tied to your customers' success, every product decision becomes clearer. The lesson is that in a world dominated by aggregators like Amazon that extract value from suppliers, there is an enormous opportunity in building tools that help those suppliers succeed independently. Sometimes the most powerful strategy is to be the arms dealer in someone else's war.",
